<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="583" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1762,2036]" pageId="2" pageNumber="583">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1867,1893]" pageId="2" pageNumber="583">Description.</emphasis>
In life, 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Hastings" authorityYear="1929" box="[437,697,1868,1894]" class="Phylactolaemata" family="Lophopodidae" genus="Lophopodella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plumatellida" pageId="2" pageNumber="583" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="capensis">
<emphasis box="[437,697,1868,1894]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="583">Lophopodella capensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a gelatinous, nontubular colony up to 
<quantity box="[1183,1263,1868,1894]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="583" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
in diameter. In typical lophopodid fashion, the zooids originate by budding at the outer periphery and gradually migrate towards the center. In this species the statoblast is distinguished by a prominent spine extending from each end and bearing minute hooks (
<figureCitation box="[362,443,1973,1999]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1913,1937]" captionTargetBox="[240,1397,1315,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-428@3.[153,1435,1295,1889]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Lophopodella statoblasts from the MRAC collection and from illustrations by Kraepelin (1914). (a) Specimen No. 201, Lophopodella capensis var. michaelseni; (b) Specimen No. 202, L. stuhlmanni with broad polar truncation; (c) L. thomasi with narrow polar truncation; (d) L. stuhlmanni (fig. 1c, d from Kraepelin, 1914). Scale bar for all statoblasts = 200 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4397991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4397991/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="583">Fig. 1a</figureCitation>
). Unfortunately, the MRAC specimen was contracted into a tight mass and could not be examined without damaging the tissues. There are no more than two statoblasts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="584" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kraepelin, K." box="[321,512,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" pagination="55 - 69" refId="ref11351" refString="Kraepelin, K. (1914) Bryozoa. In: Michaelsen, W. (Ed.), Betrage zur Kenntnis der Land- und Susswasserfauna Deutsch-Sudwestafrujas. Friederichsen, Hamburg, pp. 55 - 69." type="book chapter" year="1914">Kraepelin (1914)</bibRefCitation>
believed the 
<emphasis box="[659,793,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">michaelseni</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[799,927,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" rank="variety" variety="was">variety was</taxonomicName>
warranted by details of the statoblast: a larger number of hooks on the spine, a slight truncation at the poles, and a broader, more rounded shape of the capsule. While these features are confirmed in the MRAC material (
<figureCitation box="[832,913,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1913,1937]" captionTargetBox="[240,1397,1315,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-428@3.[153,1435,1295,1889]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Lophopodella statoblasts from the MRAC collection and from illustrations by Kraepelin (1914). (a) Specimen No. 201, Lophopodella capensis var. michaelseni; (b) Specimen No. 202, L. stuhlmanni with broad polar truncation; (c) L. thomasi with narrow polar truncation; (d) L. stuhlmanni (fig. 1c, d from Kraepelin, 1914). Scale bar for all statoblasts = 200 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4397991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4397991/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">Fig. 1a</figureCitation>
), 
<bibRefCitation author="Hastings, A. B." box="[937,1119,223,249]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" pagination="300 - 311" refId="ref10996" refString="Hastings, A. B. (1929) Notes on some little-known phylactolaematous polyzoa and description of a new species from Tahiti. Annals of the Magazine of Natural History, 10, 300 - 311. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222932908672974" type="journal article" year="1929">Hastings (1929)</bibRefCitation>
considered them to be well within the normal range of variation for this species. New material and genetic analysis should easily resolve this issue. The 
<typeStatus box="[273,321,295,321]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">type</typeStatus>
locality for 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Hastings" authorityYear="1929" box="[461,588,295,320]" class="Phylactolaemata" family="Lophopodidae" genus="Lophopodella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plumatellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="capensis">
<emphasis box="[461,588,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">L. capensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is Florida Lake in 
<collectingCountry box="[805,950,295,321]" name="South Africa" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">South Africa</collectingCountry>
, a 24 ha water body that is now part of the city park system of Johannesburg.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
